  "prompt": "Surely, money laundering is illegal, right?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or other crimes) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of transactions or financial systems. \n\nGovernments and international organizations have established strict laws and regulations to combat money laundering because it enables criminal activities to flourish, undermines the integrity of financial systems, and can have serious economic and social consequences. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, asset seizures, and imprisonment. \n\nExamples of anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks include the U.S. Bank Secrecy Act (BSA), the European Union\u2019s Anti-Money Laundering Directives, and the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations, which provide global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.",
